3.2 Market Segmentation & Type and Distribution Channel

round(prop.table(table(hotels$market_segment, hotels$is_canceled),1), 3) #Calculates cancellation rates by market segment 
##                
##                     0     1
##   Aviation      0.781 0.219
##   Complementary 0.869 0.131
##   Corporate     0.813 0.187
##   Direct        0.847 0.153
##   Groups        0.389 0.611
##   Offline TA/TO 0.657 0.343
##   Online TA     0.633 0.367
##   Undefined     0.000 1.000
round(prop.table(table(hotels$customer_type, hotels$is_canceled),1), 3) #Calculates cancellation by customer type
##                  
##                       0     1
##   Contract        0.690 0.310
##   Group           0.898 0.102
##   Transient       0.593 0.407
##   Transient-Party 0.746 0.254
round(prop.table(table(hotels$distribution_channel, hotels$is_canceled),1), 3) #Calculates cancellation rates by Channel
##            
##                 0     1
##   Corporate 0.779 0.221
##   Direct    0.825 0.175
##   GDS       0.808 0.192
##   TA/TO     0.590 0.410
##   Undefined 0.200 0.800

The cancellation rates based on market segment of the customer and the distribution channel the booking was made are quite interesting. For the market segment, the cancellation rates seem fairly consistent with the exception of Group bookings which have a cancellation rate nearly double the nearest segment (Online TA).Interestingly, when broken down into customer type, Group bookings have a much lower cancellation rate than the group market segment, a possible error is apparent in how the markets are categorized between these two measures (market segment vs customer type descriptions do not provide explanation in Kaggle).

We see a similar scenario for the distribution sample, where corporate, direct, and GDS are all similar, but TA/TO (travel agents/tour operators) channel is nearly double that of any other channel excluding the undefined customers.

The cancellation rates for each deposit type is incredible interesting. Among those with non-refundable deposits almost all of those customers ended up canceling their room (99.4%). Unless the data is labeled incorrectly, this is a very surprising findings, with almost all of those customers losing money and still canceling.

The day of month distribution for each month is interesting, showing that in a majority of the months, arrivals peak between the tenth and twentieth. It should be noted that the separation of the cancellation shows that the cancellations follow the pattern of arrivals, as in when more people are set to arrive, more cancellations occur. The proportion table affirms this finding and is provided to show the exact range of cancellation rates for each month; with a range of 30.5-41.5% of bookings are canceled each month, there appears to be little variation among the rates per month.

#Histogram of total number of guests for each hotel

Above are histograms for the number of adults, children, babies, and all guests total for each hotel. Overwhelmingly the most common amount of adults is two, likely indicating that people typically travel as a couple or partnership. Since such a large portion of people travel without children or babies, the children and babies histogram start at 1. Most bookings with children only have 1, while the proportion of people have two children is much closer to one child for the resort hotel, possibly due to more people traveling to the resort for non-business purposes. For babies, it is overwhelmingly dominated by having only one baby for a booking. Besides the number of children distinction already mentioned, the distributions for each hotel are quite similar.

4.2 Meals

# Seeing the type of meals families with kids buy
kids <- hotels %>%
  filter(children > 1)

meals_with_kids <- data.frame(table(kids$meal))

meals_with_kids <- meals_with_kids %>%
  mutate(meal_percent = round(Freq / nrow(kids), 3)*100) %>%
  rename(meal_type = Var1, number_of_meals = Freq)
meals_with_kids
##   meal_type number_of_meals meal_percent
## 1        BB            3183         85.4
## 2        FB              12          0.3
## 3        HB             489         13.1
## 4        SC              31          0.8
## 5 Undefined              14          0.4
ggplot(meals_with_kids, aes(x="", y=meal_percent, fill=meal_type)) +
  geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity", color = "white") +
  coord_polar('y', start = 0) +
  geom_text(aes(y = meal_percent, label=meal_percent), position=position_stack(vjust=0.5), color = "black") +
  theme_void() +
  labs(title = "Perentage of Meals Bought by Adults with Kids")

# Seeing the type of meals families with no kids buy
no_kids <- hotels %>%
  filter(children == 0)

meals_with_no_kids <- data.frame(table(no_kids$meal))

meals_with_no_kids <- meals_with_no_kids %>%
  mutate(meal_percent = round(Freq / nrow(no_kids), 3)*100) %>%
  rename(meal_type = Var1, number_of_meals = Freq)
meals_with_no_kids
##   meal_type number_of_meals meal_percent
## 1        BB           85227         76.9
## 2        FB             732          0.7
## 3        HB           13217         11.9
## 4        SC           10494          9.5
## 5 Undefined            1126          1.0
ggplot(meals_with_no_kids, aes(x="", y=meal_percent, fill=meal_type)) +
  geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity", color = "white") +
  coord_polar('y', start = 0) +
  geom_text(aes(y = meal_percent, label=meal_percent), position=position_stack(vjust=0.5), color = "black") +
  theme_void() +
  labs(title = "Perentage of Meals Bought by Adults with No Kids")

From these pie charts we can see a notable difference between families who had kids and families who did not have kids when buying meals. The top meal choice of Bed & Breakfast did not change between groups, but the percentage bought did have a marked change. For the adults with kids, 85.4% bought the BB choice, while only 76.9% bought the BB choice. It seems that the adults with no kids group had a larger portion opt out of a meal choice (SC with 9.5% and Undefined with 1%) than the group of adults that had kids. This could show that the adults without kids are able to get meals in any means they see necessary, while the adults with kids would probably want convenience over everything while having more mouth to feed.

4.3 Agent Bookings

# Calculating the average daily rate of bookings that did/didn't use an agent
mean_adr_agent <- hotels %>%
  filter(agent != 'NULL') %>%
  summarize(mean_adr_agent = round(mean(adr, na.rm = TRUE), 2))

mean_adr_no_agent <- hotels %>%
  filter(agent == 'NULL') %>%
  summarize(mean_adr_no_agent = round(mean(adr, na.rm = TRUE), 2))

mean_adr_agent
##   mean_adr_agent
## 1         104.62
mean_adr_no_agent
##   mean_adr_no_agent
## 1             84.25

These numbers show us that, people booked with an agent actually paid more per night on average than those that did not book with an agent. If you used and agent, you would have paid $104.62 while if you did not use an agent, you would have paid $84.25.
